<h1>Buttons</h1>
<p>
	Buttons provide a way for users to interact with our applications.
	They can contain text, icons, or both and come in three different sizes: standard, squished, and stretched.
	To help with the CTA hierarchy on a screen buttons can be displayed as primary (filled), secondary (outlined),
	or just text (no container). Choosing the right button style ties directly to the importance of it in relation
	to the content around it on the screen.
</p>
<p>
	The HTML <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> element represents a clickable button.
	It provides a way for a user to interact with the application. Add <code class="format-code">.wds-button</code>
	class to apply Fandom Design System styling. This results with a default Primary button.
	There are two more base variants: Secondary and Text.
</p>
<p>
	Passing additional <code>disabled</code> attribute will change button's styling and functionality.
	This Boolean attribute indicates that the user cannot interact with the button.
	Other <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/button#Attributes">
	valid HTML attributes</a> may be passed as well.
</p>
<p>
	Buttons can contain icons with text.
</p>

<section>
	<h2 id="primary">Primary buttons</h2>
	<p>Default version for general use.</p>
	{{#component-demo name='buttons'}}
		{{#wds-button}}Primary button{{/wds-button}}
		{{#wds-button}}
			{{wds-icon name='fandom-heart' size='small'}}
			<span>Primary button</span>
		{{/wds-button}}
		{{#wds-button disabled=true}}Primary disabled{{/wds-button}}
	{{/component-demo}}

	<h2>Parameters</h2>
	<div>
		<h3>HBS Properties</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>disabled</strong> (bool): whether button should be disabled or not</li>
			<li><strong>secondary</strong> (bool): whether button should be secondary or not</li>
			<li><strong>text</strong> (bool): whether button should be of type text or not</li>
			<li><strong>square</strong> (bool): whether button should be square or not</li>
			<li><strong>class</strong> (string): additional class names</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	<div>
		<h3>HTML Attributes/CSS Classes</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>wds-is-secondary</strong>: whether button should be secondary or not</li>
			<li><strong>wds-is-text</strong>: whether button should be of type text or not</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
</section>

<section>
	<h2 id="secondary">Secondary buttons</h2>
	<p>Adding class <code class="format-code">.wds-is-secondary</code> changes the button's looks. It is used to create
		a button that draws less user's attention.</p>
	{{#component-demo name='buttons-secondary'}}
		{{#wds-button secondary=true}}Secondary button{{/wds-button}}
		{{#wds-button secondary=true}}
			{{wds-icon name='fandom-heart' size='small'}}
			<span>Secondary button</span>
		{{/wds-button}}
		{{#wds-button secondary=true disabled=true}}Secondary disabled{{/wds-button}}
	{{/component-demo}}
</section>

